{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566300"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:38:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:38:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18787"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18787"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.14,0.59,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78624"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18787"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"8805"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39585"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78624"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe bilateral eye pain and photophobia that began six hours ago. He reported skiing yesterday and denies any trauma or falls, though states he forgot to wear his ski goggles. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His vital signs are within normal limits. Both eyes are red and watery with excessive blinking. Visual acuity is 6/9 in both eyes. Fluorescein staining reveals punctate epithelial erosions on both corneas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Oral acyclovir","Eye patch","Topical lubricants","Topical steroids"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of photokeratitis (\u0022welder\u0027s flash\u0022), which occurs when the corneal epithelium is damaged by ultraviolet radiation. The condition is painful but self-limiting, typically resolving within 24-48 hours. It can occur secondary to arc welding, sun lamps, laboratory UV lights, damaged metal halide lamps and snow reflections (especially at high altitude with snow reflection). The UV damages the epithelium to reveal the sub-epithelial nerve plexus and resulting severe pain, up to 12 hours after exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical lubricants\u003C/strong\u003E and oral analgesia is the most appropriate management. This provides symptomatic relief while the corneal epithelium naturally heals. Cool compresses may also help alleviate discomfort. The patient should be advised to strictly comply with protective eyewear in the future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient given the severe pain and discomfort the patient is experiencing. Active management with lubricants and pain relief is necessary for patient comfort during the healing process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for herpes simplex keratitis, but this patient\u0027s history of UV exposure and bilateral involvement makes viral keratitis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E are contraindicated in epithelial defects as they can delay healing and increase the risk of infection. They play no role in the management of acute photokeratitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eeye patch\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it may increase discomfort, delay healing and is unnecessary. Bilateral involvement also makes patching impractical. The cornea will heal naturally with appropriate lubrication and pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention is crucial in photokeratitis. All welders should wear appropriate protective equipment with UV filters. Similarly, individuals exposed to snow or water reflections should wear UV-protective sunglasses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Photokeratitis is a painful, self-limiting condition caused by UV exposure to the cornea, commonly from welding or snow reflection.","Treatment of photokeratitis is supportive, focusing on pain relief and lubricating drops while the corneal epithelium heals.","Topical antibiotics are not routinely indicated in photokeratitis unless there is evidence of secondary infection."],"references":["Patel R et. al. Phtokeratitis. American Academy of Opthalmology. 2024.  Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Photokeratitis","Izadi M, Jafari N, Pourazizi M, Ansari M. Photokeratitis induced by ultraviolet radiation in travelers: A major health problem.  Journal of Postgraduate Medicine. 2017.   Available at: https://researchgate.net/publication/320562256_Photokeratitis_induced_by_ultraviolet_radiation_in_travelers_A_major_health_problem"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18787"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63966"}